	abstract = {South Asia's cereal-based farming is under growing pressure from climate change, resource depletion, and agri-food and nutrition insecurity. This study evaluated six diversified, low-input, conservation agriculture (CA)-based systems as sustainable alternatives to the rice-wheat conventional tillage (RW-CT) system across 353 ha in 597 agroecosystems over two years. Performance indicators included productivity, greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, energy-use efficiency (EUE), water footprint, and soil health. Compared with RW-CT, alternative systems lowered GHG-emissions by 12–65 %, improved productivity by 13–42 %, and profitability by ∼66 %. Energy performance varied: maize–mustard–green gram (MMG) achieved the highest energy output (227,988.1 MJ ha<sup>−1</sup>); maize–lentil–green gram (MLG) showed strong input–output efficiency; finger millet–maize–green gram (FMG) was most resource-efficient, cutting emissions by nearly half with minimal inputs. Soil fertility improved significantly, with soil organic carbon up ∼37 % and available nitrogen ∼8 %. Diversified maize- and millet-based CA-systems thus provide a climate-resilient, resource-efficient pathway for South Asia's agricultural production system. © 2025},
