	affiliations = {Jiangsu Key Laboratory of Crop Genetics and Physiology/Jiangsu Key Laboratory of Crop Cultivation and Physiology, Agricultural College of Yangzhou University, Yangzhou, 225009, China; Jiangsu Co-Innovation Center for Modern Production Technology of Grain Crops, Yangzhou University, Yangzhou, 225009, China; Research Institute of Rice Industrial Engineering Technology, Yangzhou University, Yangzhou, 225009, China; State Key Laboratory of Herbage Improvement and Grassland Agroecosystems, College of Ecology, Lanzhou University, Gansu, Lanzhou, 730000, China},
	abstract = {Agricultural management practices (AMPs) have the potential to significantly enhance crop yield, albeit with the possible side effect of escalating greenhouse gas emissions. Few studies have undertaken a comprehensive quantification of the impact of AMPs on crop production and soil GHG, particularly in identifying the optimal AMPs for rice cultivation within rice-wheat rotation system. Here, we combined data analysis and keyword search methods on 1433 individual experimental observations from 172 studies on diverse soil types in the subtropical monsoon climate zone of China to assess the impact of AMPs on rice yield, CH<sub>4</sub> and N<sub>2</sub>O emissions, total greenhouse gas emissions (TGHGE). We focused on four key AMPs: mineral N fertilizer management (including ordinary N fertilizer and slow−/controlled-release fertilizer (SCRF)), organic material management (incorporating organic fertilizer, biochar amendment, and straw return), water-saving irrigation, and no-tillage. Our result showed the rice yield ranged from 2525 to 31,196 kg ha<sup>−1</sup>, and mineral N fertilizer and organic material management boosted rice yield by 2.84–16.19 % and 2.47–8.52 %, respectively. In terms of N<sub>2</sub>O emissions, biochar amendment resulted in a decrease of 13.05 %, while ordinary N fertilizer, organic fertilizer, and water-saving irrigation led to increases of 63.16 %, 136.66 %, and 37.41 %, respectively. The implementation of SCRF, water-saving irrigation, and no-tillage significantly curtailed CH<sub>4</sub> (6.83 %–35.91 %) and TGHGE (6.22 %–20.59 %). Conversely, organic fertilizer and straw return significantly escalated CH<sub>4</sub> emissions by 102.20 % and 33.64 % and TGHGE by 85.03 % and 32.40 %. Rice yield and GHG emissions are mainly influenced by variables such as soil bulk density, pH, soil organic carbon, soil texture, mean annual temperature, and total nitrogen. Our study demonstrates that the application of SCRF, water-saving irrigation, and no-tillage can effectively reduce GHG without compromising yield. These practices are particularly effective under climatic and soil conditions of rice-wheat rotation systems in China, thereby contributing to the sustainable rice farming. © 2024 Elsevier B.V.},
	author_keywords = {Agricultural management practices; Methane; Nitrous oxide; Rice yield; Rice–wheat rotation system},
	keywords = {China; Crop rotation; Gas emissions; Greenhouse gases; Nitrogen oxides; Organic carbon; Rotation; Search engines; Soils; Textures; Water conservation; charcoal; fertilizer; methane; nitrogen; nitrogen fertilizer; nitrous oxide; organic carbon; organic fertilizer; slow controlled release fertilizer; unclassified drug; methane; mineral; nitrous oxide; water; Agricultural management practice; CH 4; Greenhouse gas emissions; N fertilizers; Nitrous oxide; Rice yield; Rice-wheat rotations; Rice–wheat rotation system; Slow/controlled release; Water-saving irrigation; agricultural emission; agricultural management; alternative agriculture; biochar; crop production; crop rotation; crop yield; emission control; environmental economics; greenhouse gas; management practice; methane; nitrous oxide; rice; soil amendment; soil emission; sustainable development; zero tillage; agricultural management; air pollution control; Article; bulk density; carbon footprint; China; controlled study; crop rotation; data analysis; fertilizer application; greenhouse gas emission; harvest; irrigation (agriculture); monsoon climate; no tillage; nonhuman; rice; soil acidity; soil amendment; soil chemistry; soil property; soil temperature; soil texture; sustainable agriculture; water conservation; wheat; agricultural worker; article; crop production; harvest; methane emission; nitrous oxide emission; pH; rotation; straw; temperature; Cultivation},
