	abstract = {The substantial environmental footprint of construction sector necessitates the development of sustainable material alternatives that support circular economy principles and reduce carbon emissions. This study explores the transformation of rice husk ash (RHA), an underutilized agricultural byproduct, into value-added rice husk ash aggregates (RHAA) via cold-bonding pelletization. A mix incorporating RHA (50–80 %), ground granulated blast furnace slag (10–40 %), and ordinary portland cement (10 %) was evaluated under varying pelletization parameters (disc angles: 18°, 36°, 54° speeds: 20, 30, 40 rpm) and curing durations (7–56 days). The resulting RHAA demonstrated oven-dry bulk densities ranging from 595 to 698 kg/m<sup>3</sup>, satisfying ASTM C330 standards for structural lightweight aggregate. Comprehensive tests—including particle compressive strength, ten percent fines value, water absorption, and specific gravity—indicated that a 50 % RHA content yielded optimal physical performance. While RHA-based concrete exhibited moderate reductions in mechanical strength, the findings underscore the potential of RHAA to reduce natural resource extraction and landfill waste. This research contributes to advancing eco-efficient construction materials and supports scalable strategies for sustainable building engineering, particularly in the valorization of industrial and agricultural residues. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
