	abstract = {The concepts of water footprint are applied to determine the consumption of water, direct or indirect for water budget of a region. The Ganges basin is an important densely populated, highly fertile agricultural landscape in South Asia. The present chapter provides an extensive discussion of the existing scenario of water footprint in the Ganges basin. In the follow-up, the three basic components of water footprint, that is, green, blue, and gray color, are explored to understand water productivity and consumption. Further, water footprint of crops and livestock is discussed. Sustainable water management practices are explored to provide feasible water balance and budgeting strategies. In South Asia, the Ganges and Indus basins alone account for ~25% of the world’s total water footprint. The study reveals that rice and wheat cultivation account for the major water footprint crops in the Ganges region. Moreover, the largest green and blue water footprints are found in the state of Uttar Pradesh, India. Indeed, by determining the water efficiency for commodity supply chains, the influential factors fostering the water consumption and implementation of sustainable management solutions will be useful to restore water security in the region. The interstate virtual water trade may exacerbate water scarcity rather than water endowment. Moreover, by assessing the efficacy of water footprint, approaches can be useful in framing essential policies for reducing water scarcity. © 2025 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.},
	author_keywords = {crops; Ganga River; livestock; Water footprint; water security},
	keywords = {Budget control; Cultivation; Ecology; Sustainable development; Water conservation; Ecological services; Ganga river; ITS applications; River basins; South Asia; Water budget; Water consumption; Water footprint; Water scarcity; Water security; Crops},
	publisher = {Elsevier},
