	year = {2026},
	journal = {Climate-Resilient Agriculture for Sustainable Crop Production: New Adaptation and Mitigation Strategies},
	pages = {129 - 154},
	doi = {10.1201/9781998511150-5},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105027616280?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {AICRP on Seed (Crops), Department of Plant Breeding of Genetics, Faculty of Agriculture, Assam Agricultural University, Assam, Jorhat, India; Department of Seed Science and Technology, Faculty of Agriculture, Uttar Banga Krishi Vishwavidyalaya, West Bengal, Pundibari, India; AICRP on Crops, Department of Plant Breeding and Genetics, Faculty of Agriculture, Assam Agricultural University, Assam, Jorhat, India; Department of Plant Breeding and Genetics, Faculty of Agriculture, Assam Agricultural University, Assam, Jorhat, India; Department of Agronomy, Dr. Rajendra Prasad Central Agricultural University, Bihar, Pusa, India; Department of Agricultural Sciences and Technology, School of Agriculture and Environmental Sciences, Kenyatta University, Nairobi, Kenya},
	abstract = {Poverty and hunger, particularly among populations whose diets consist mainly of cereals and lack micronutrients, pose a serious global threat. Millets possess unique nutritional properties, including complex carbohydrates, dietary fiber, phenolic compounds, and phytochemicals with therapeutic benefits. They also naturally contain essential nutrients such as iron, zinc, and calcium, making them a viable solution to malnutrition. Climate change has become a major factor limiting agricultural yields, especially in grain production. In this context, millets are increasingly recognized for their climate resilience compared to other grains. The adverse effects of climate change, though variable across regions, are particularly severe in developing countries like India, where food insecurity is a major concern. Millets contribute to climate change mitigation due to their lower carbon footprint—substantially less than that of wheat and rice, which emit 3968 and 3401 kg of CO2 equivalents per hectare, respectively. Known as “nutri-cereals” or “smart foods,” millets are well adapted to a range of climatic conditions and thrive in resource-constrained environments with limited water. As such, they support sustainable food systems and offer a practical alternative to conventional cereals. Promoting millet cultivation is essential to addressing hunger, improving nutrition, and enhancing food security in a changing climate. © 2026 by Apple Academic Press, Inc.},
