	abstract = {Sustainable agriculture with limited land and water is difficult as the global population is about to approach 9 billion by 2050. Conventional carbon, water, and labor-intensive crop establishment techniques reduce soil health, groundwater levels, and overall land, and water productivity. Conventional agricultural practices and global warming adversely affected overall food and ecology. Farmers use more water, fertilizers, and pesticides to boost yields, which consequently increases greenhouse gas emissions, and soil and water pollution. CO2, CH4, and N2O leaks must be prevented to reduce climate change and boost input use efficiency in a sustainable and climate-smart way. Efficient crop residue management techniques must be propagated among the farmers to reduce field fire incidences. Food loss and waste reduction reduce the pressure for growing more and more from the limited rather than shrinking natural resources. Resource conservation technologies viz. minimum tillage, precision land leveling, tensiometer-guided rice irrigations, un-puddled direct seeded rice, and bed planting must be demonstrated in the region to reduce carbon, water, and footprints for practicing sustainable and climate-smart agriculture in the tropics. © 2025 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.},
