	affiliations = {State Key Laboratory of Soil and Sustainable Agriculture, Institute of Soil Science, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Nanjing, 211135, China; University of Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing, 100049, China},
	abstract = {The aim of high crop productivity in large-scale rice farming systems demands intensive fertilizer, water, and energy inputs. This leads to high environmental cost and a low ecological index. This study is aimed to evaluate the potential of the recently developed root zone precision nitrogen (N) management (RN) on the agronomic and sustainability performance in the intensive rice production system with life cycle assessment (LCA). A three-year (2021–2023) field trial with an advanced RN strategy was conducted to evaluate crop productivity, economic income, N and carbon (C) footprints, energy flow, and ecosystem economic benefits (EEB) at Huanghai Farm ─ a large-scale farming site. The RN was more proficient in terms of farm economics and environmental perspective, as it increased grain yield (4.0–11.6 %), net return (NR) (16.6–32.3 %), and energy productivity (11.2–13.9 %) compared to farmers’ practice (FP). The RN reduced N footprints for per unit of yield (57.1–57.9 %) and NR (63.1 %–64.9 %). The C footprints for per unit of yield (38.0–38.2 %) and NR (46.7–48.5 %) were also reduced due to reduced NH<sub>3</sub> volatilization, N<sub>2</sub>O, and CH<sub>4</sub> emissions. The EEB increased by 122.3–152.5 % because of reductions in labor, ecosystem, and human health costs. The RN at the rate of 300 kg N ha<sup>-</sup>¹ was found most appropriate for its integrative benefits. These results suggest that optimizing fertilizer application through RN technology can be an effective N management strategy to promote the sustainability of large-scale rice farms. Furthermore, this technology holds promise for adoption in other cropping systems and low-yielding regions. © 2026},
