	pages = {4497 - 4512},
	doi = {10.26848/rbgf.v18.6.p4497-4512},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105022188658?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Universidade Federal de Sergipe, Brazil; Faculdade Estácio de Sá de Ourinhos, Universidade Federal do Piauí (UFPI), Brazil},
	abstract = {Environmental indicators are essential for ensuring the sustainable use of natural resources and the Water Footprint (WF) methodology helps identify unsustainable practices in food agroindustries. In the Lower São Francisco region of Sergipe (LSF), rice cultivation (Oryza sativa L.) is predominant, highlighting the importance of agroindustrial practices that aim to minimize both direct and indirect environmental impacts on water bodies. In this context, the objective of this article is to determine the WF of an agroindustry processing rice produced in the LSF, using data from a processing plant located in the city of Telha – SE for the 2021-2022 harvest. A qualitative-quantitative approach was used to quantify the blue and grey WF according to the methodology proposed by Hoekstra et al. (2011). Analysis of the results obtained showed that the average water consumption corresponding to the processing of 300 tons of grains was 4,887.51 m³ t<sup>-1</sup>, with a low blue water consumption, accounting for 42% of the total, reflecting the processing method used at the plant, and a higher contribution from the grey WF (58%), with elevated consumption in November 2021, indicating the pollution potential of the grain processing system. The quantification of the WF in rice processing in the Lower São Francisco region is essential for analyzing the efficiency of production processes, providing critical data for technical adjustments aimed at optimizing water resource use. This highlights the need for individual water meters to monitor water intake and the adoption of appropriate wastewater treatment systems to ensure the proper disposal of final residues. © 2025, Universidade Federal de Pernambuco. All rights reserved.},
