	affiliations = {University of Cross River-Mechanical Engineering Department, Calabar, Nigeria; University of Uyo-Mechanical & Aerospace Engineering Department, Uyo, Nigeria; Mechanical Engineering Science, University of Johannesburg, Johannesburg, South Africa},
	abstract = {Geopolymers are known to have a lower carbon footprint than Portland cement and are synthesized by activating an aluminosilicate source with an alkali solution. These activators especially those from silicates contribute negatively to several other environmental indices and are difficult to handle, thus the need to search for alternative sources. Several sources of biomass are known to possess a very high quantity of silica that can be leached out of the source. This research investigates the effect of utilising leachates obtained from rice husk ash (RHA), sugar cane leaves ash (SCLA), plantain leaves ash (PLA), coconut leaves ash (CLA) and maize husk ash (MHA). A factorial design of experiments was developed, taking into consideration two levels of biomass content (5g, 10g) and five levels of biomass leachate (RHA, SCLA, PLA, CLA and MHA). Physical properties such as bulk density and water absorption rate were investigated while flexural and compressive strength were investigated for mechanical properties. The control sample was made with a mixture of NaOH and Na2SiO3 activators and compared with the results obtained from other leachates. The results showed that binders produced with RHA leachates possessed better mechanical properties than other investigated biomass sources. The compressive and flexural strength of the control sample at 28 days of testing age was 17.87 MPa and 4.1 MPa respectively. These values were 14% and 11% higher than those obtained from the RHA leachate. The pareto chart showed that the weight of the biomass source had a significant effect on the flexural but not the compressive strength of the binder. © 2023 American Institute of Physics Inc.. All rights reserved.},
	author_keywords = {Alkaline activators; Biomass; Environmental impact; Geopolymer; Leachates},
