	affiliations = {Department of Civil Engineering, Aarupadai Veedu Institute of Technology, Vinayaka Mission's Research Foundation, Chennai, India},
	abstract = {Geopolymer concrete, a sustainable substitute for Ordinary Portland Cement (OPC), has traditionally relied on commercial alkali activators like sodium hydroxide and sodium silicate, which are costly and environmentally detrimental. This study investigates the technical feasibility of using desulfurization dust (DeS-dust) from the steel industry and sodium silicate extracted from rice husk ash (RHA-SS) as sustainable replacements for commercial activators in Fly Ash-Ground Granulated Blast Furnace Slag (FA-GGBS)-based geopolymer concrete. These alternative activators aim to mitigate the environmental footprint and costs associated with commercial activators. The viability of using industrial wastes such as DeS-dust and RHA-SS was confirmed through pH, Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR), Energy Dispersive X-ray analysis (EDAX) and acid titration analyses. The DRG100 mix, comprising 60 % FA and 40 % GGBS as precursors activated with RHA-extracted sodium silicate solution and DeS-dust, demonstrated remarkable improvements in mechanical and durability properties. This mix completely replaced commercial activators with waste-sourced alternative activators. The compressive strength of DRG100 reached 48.24 MPa, a 27.23 % increase compared to the control sample with traditional activators (37.9 MPa). In addition, DRG100 exhibited a 15.6 % improvement in split tensile strength (5.26 MPa) and a 12.1 % increase in flexural strength (5.82 MPa) compared to the control sample. These significant improvements in mechanical properties underline the effectiveness of the alternative activators. Durability was also enhanced, with water absorption reduced by 13.3 % and chloride ion permeability decreased by 57.1 %, indicating a denser microstructure and greater resistance to environmental factors. Thermal stability tests revealed that DRG100 retained 86.2 % of its weight and maintained a residual compressive strength of 24.2 MPa at 900°C, outperforming the control mix. Furthermore, the cost analysis revealed a 67.9 % reduction in production costs for DRG100 compared to the control sample, highlighting the economic benefits of using these alternative activators. Thus, using alternative activators presents a novel advancement in the production of geopolymer concrete, tackling environmental challenges while enhancing mechanical properties, durability, and cost efficiency. This study paves the way for more sustainable construction practices by reducing reliance on non-renewable resources and promoting industrial and agricultural waste usage in geopolymer concrete production. Thus, making geopolymer concrete a more eco-friendly and economically viable option for widespread application. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
