	abstract = {Catalysts prepared from wastes (such as industrial wastewater, agricultural wastewater, or municipal wastewater) have recently been proposed as a new alternative to catalyze sustainable H2 production and other industrial processes in line with the circular economy principle. Sourced from fly ash, red mud, rice husk, and e-waste, this chemical-rich material acts as the catalyst to facilitate cost-effective water splitting, biogas reforming, and degradation of pollutants by reducing the dependence on costly virgin materials. They bring added value to industrial processes and may help reduce carbon footprints by adding value to waste streams rich in silica, alumina, and precious metals, like, for example, platinum and palladium. However, commercialization is limited: large differences in waste composition, regulation compliance, and market acceptance are hampered by reliability issues. Cost- and environment-effectiveness is demonstrated from favorable case studies of zeolite from fly ash and biochar catalysts from agricultural waste in petrochemicals and renewable fuels. Hybrid-nanostructured catalysts with the support of friendly policies like EPR can contribute to their potential. Concerning the problem of scale-up and standardization of the waste-derived catalysts, the technology would be able to contribute to the sustainable development of related industries, reduce environmental pollution, and promote the construction of a resource-conserving society. © 2026 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.},
