	affiliations = {Agronomy College, Jilin Agricultural University, Changchun, 130118, China; Agronomy College, Heilongjiang Bayi Agricultural University, Daqing, 163000, China},
	abstract = {To address the development dilemma of "high yield, high resource consumption" in the cold-region rice cropping areas of Northeast China and to respond to the national "dual carbon" strategy, this study aimed to systematically evaluate the sustainability of different rice cultivation models by integrating water, carbon, energy, and economic footprints. The goal was to identify an optimized path that balances food security, environmental friendliness, and economic feasibility. A field experiment was conducted from 2019 to 2020 in Changchun, Jilin Province, comparing four cultivation models: traditional transplanted flooded rice (TFR), wet direct-seeded flooded rice (WDSF), dry direct-seeded flooded rice (DDSF), and dry direct-seeded rice with alternate wetting and drying (DDSA). A comprehensive evaluation framework was established, incorporating water footprint (WF), carbon footprint (CF), energy footprint (EF), and net ecosystem economic benefit (NEEB). A bivariate sensitivity analysis was introduced to explore the impact of carbon and rice price fluctuations on economic decision-making. The DDSA model exhibited the optimal environmental performance, with its total water and carbon footprints reducing by 42.4% and 29.6%, respectively, compared to TFR. This was primarily attributed to a 95% reduction in methane (CH<sub>4</sub>) emissions and significant blue water savings. However, it suffered from a significant yield loss and increased nitrous oxide (N<sub>2</sub>O) emissions, revealing a trade-off between CH<sub>4</sub>and N<sub>2</sub>O emissions. Although the DDSF model showed considerable emission reduction potential, its severe yield loss led to the poorest NEEB, highlighting a sharp conflict between environmental improvement and economic viability. The WDSF model maintained a relatively high yield while achieving the highest NEEB (a 5.9% increase over TFR), demonstrating the best overall benefits. Sensitivity analysis indicated that the NEEB of the WDSF model remained the highest across carbon prices (0–300 CNY t<sup>-1</sup>CO<sub>2</sub>-eq) and rice price fluctuations (±20%), exhibiting high robustness. Under scenarios of normal rice prices with a carbon price exceeding 250 CNY t<sup>-1</sup>CO<sub>2</sub>-eq, or a 20% drop in rice prices, the economic competitiveness of the DDSA model would surpass that of TFR. Under the conditions of this study, based on the four-dimensional assessment, the WDSF model achieves synergistic optimization of environmental and economic benefits while ensuring a relatively high yield, making it the most feasible and balanced model for promoting the sustainable transformation of cold-region rice cultivation at present. Future efforts should focus on enhancing the yield of dry direct-seeded rice through technological breakthroughs and leveraging policy levers such as carbon pricing to activate the economic value of its environmental benefits, ultimately promoting the transition of cold-region rice production towards a sustainable, "eco-value-added" paradigm. © 2026 The Authors.},
	author_keywords = {Carbon footprint; Cold-region rice cropping; Direct-seeded rice; Energy footprint; Net ecosystem economic benefit; Rice cultivation models; Sustainability assessment; Water footprint},
	keywords = {Changchun; China; China; Jilin; Cost effectiveness; Decision making; Economic analysis; Economic and social effects; Ecosystems; Environmental management; Nitrogen oxides; Sensitivity analysis; Sustainable development; Cold regions; Cold-region rice cropping; Cultivation models; Direct-seeded rice; Economic benefits; Energy; Energy footprint; Net ecosystem economic benefit; Rice cultivation; Rice cultivation model; Sustainability assessment; Water footprint; carbon footprint; cost-benefit analysis; cropping practice; cultivation; rice; sustainability; water footprint; Carbon footprint},
