	abstract = {The major bottleneck of dairy effluent treatment plant (ETP) operation is the generation of 10 m3 of nutrient-rich wastewater per liter of milk processed resulting in an annual production of 7.93 tons of carbon dioxide equivalent (CO2 e) gas during treatment in a 7- to 8-step process requiring 105hours, with lipid-rich sludge generation through an expensive, non-eco-friendly, laborious process that is often not adoptable by the small segment installations. A carefully selected tailor-made microbial consortia could result in the biotransformation of this large volume of wastewater into a valuable by-product (liquid biofertilizer) with the minimum carbon footprint. Such microbial systems are stable over years under environmental conditions, maintaining its integrity. This approach makes dairy ETP operation eco-friendly, economical, and self-sustainable, ensuring minimum wastage of fresh water (for agriculture) with enhanced food production. © 2025 Elsevier Inc. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.},
