	abstract = {Background and aims: High-altitude organic rice systems face persistent trade-offs among yield, resource use efficiency, and environmental impacts, further exacerbated by chilling stress and water scarcity. Plastic mulch technology shows potential to achieve high yield and resource use efficiency in such environments, but its systematic effects on the tripartite trade-offs in high-altitude organic rice remain unclear. Methods: A three-year field experiment was conducted to compare conventional transplanting (CT) with two integrated plastic mulch rice management (IPMRM) practices: transplanted rice with plastic mulch (PMT) and direct-seeded rice with plastic mulch (PMD). We sustainably assessed yield, resource use efficiency (fertilizer use efficiency (PFP) and water use efficiency (WUE, IWUE)), environmental impacts (paddy nutrient runoff losses and greenhouse gas emissions), and economic performance (total cost and cost components, economic efficiency). Results: IPMRM transformed trade-offs into measurable synergies: it increased grain yield by 4.82% on average across the two planting methods, while simultaneously reducing the environmental footprint by cutting greenhouse gas emissions (GWP) by 31.71% and nutrient runoff losses (e.g., DTN) by 39–46%. These gains were accompanied by a 110.32% improvement in nitrogen use efficiency and a 19.84% reduction in total input costs. Conclusions: IPMRM effectively transforms trade-offs into measurable synergies, offering a climate-resilient strategy for sustainable intensification of future high-altitude organic rice systems. In the IPMRM framework, the PMT system showed greater resilience and stability across variable climatic conditions, whereas PMD offered obvious advantages in water-limited environments. © 2026 Elsevier B.V.},
	author_keywords = {Economic Efficiency; High-altitude agriculture; Organic rice; Plastic mulch; Sustainable intensification; Trade-offs},
	keywords = {agricultural intensification; alternative agriculture; climate conditions; economic analysis; environmental impact; greenhouse gas; mulching; plastic; resource use; rice; trade-off; water use efficiency},
