	affiliations = {College of Land Science and Technology, China Agricultural University, State Key Laboratory of Efficient Utilization of Agricultural Water Resources, Beijing, 100193, China; Institute of Plant Protection and Soil Fertilizer, Hubei Academy of Agricultural Sciences, Key Laboratory of Fertilization from Agricultural Wastes, Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs, Wuhan, 430064, China; Biosystems Engineering Department, Auburn University, Auburn, 36849, AL, United States; Institute of Agricultural Resources and Environment, Sichuan Academy of Agricultural Sciences, Chengdu, 610066, China},
	abstract = {CONTEXT: The ground cover rice production system (GCRPS) offers significant advantages in water savings and reducing greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions, however, its yield and environmental risk is significantly affected by rainfall. OBJECTIVE: To evaluate the comprehensive environmental impact of GCRPS by incorporating agronomic and precipitation factors for further optimize water management. METHODS: The simulation results of WHCNS (soil water heat carbon nitrogen simulator) model from field experiment were combined with the life cycle assessment methodology to evaluate yield-scaled water, nitrogen, and carbon footprint (WF, NF, and CF) of Paddy and GCRPS under different precipitation year types. Additionally, water management optimizations for GHG emission reduction in the GCRPS were identified through scenario analysis. RESULTS AND CONCLUSIONS: Compared to Paddy, GCRPS reduced WF (9 %–48 %), NF (8 %–69 %), and CF (37 %–83 %) for all precipitation year types, but GCRPS reduced yields (3.6 %–4.6 %) in wet years. Compared to local farmer irrigation practices for GCRPS, rainfed, irrigating at 50 % and 75 % of farmer's practices demonstrated minimal effect on yields across wet, normal, and dry years, and reduced the maximum WF (0.5 %–5.3 %), NF (1.7 %–15.2 %), and CF (1.1 %–10.4 %), respectively. The GCRPS demonstrated significant advantages in water saving and GHG emission reduction with little yield reduction. Rainfed, and irrigating at 50 %, and 75 % of local farmers' irrigation practice being the recommended optimal strategies for wet, normal, and dry years, respectively. SIGNIFICANCE: Our results highlight the necessity of water optimization in GCRPS to achieve sustainable development. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
