	abstract = {As China advances its “dual carbon” goals and food security strategy, its food system faces growing challenges from resource constraints and environmental pressures. In view of the current lack of research on the systematic optimization of crop planting structure at the regional scale under the coordinated control of water resources, energy consumption and carbon emissions, this paper constructs a comprehensive optimization framework for the goal of “water saving - energy saving - low carbon". Taking the planting structure of rice, wheat, and corn as decision variables, and incorporating constraints of water security, land security, and food security, the model is applied to the Beijing-Tianjin-Hebei region using historical data from 2000 to 2022. The results indicate that, during this period, the region's blue water footprint, energy consumption, and carbon emissions from grain production all showed a fluctuating downward trend. Among the crops, corn demonstrated the highest adaptability to regional water conditions and the most efficient use of resources. After optimization, the blue water footprint could be reduced by 2.987 billion m<sup>3</sup>, energy consumption by 189,500 tons of standard coal, and carbon emissions by an equivalent 678,800 tons. Although optimal planting structures vary across sub-regions, the overall trend points toward reduced wheat and increased corn cultivation. This framework provides a novel approach to crop structure optimization under multi-resource constraints and offers practical guidance for advancing sustainable agriculture and food security in metropolitan regions. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.},
