	abstract = {Agriculture is the underappreciated backbone of the global economy. Food products like wheat, rice, and corn and non-food products like cotton and jute are both critical for the survival of humanity and unhindered economic activity. Considering the water and carbon footprint of agricultural products, it is prudent that its resources should be utilized to the greatest extent possible. This need leads to the valorization of agrobiomass. Agrobiomass valorization fits perfectly like a piece of a jigsaw puzzle at the intersection of concepts of sustainability, circular economy, and circular bioeconomy. Understanding these concepts and their interrelationships is vital not only for policymakers but also for the general populace to have a holistic picture of what agrobiomass valorization is. This chapter also covers the types of agrobiomass valorization and the classification of agrobiomass. The chapter culminates with a summary and conclusion. © 2025 selection and editorial matter, Sankha Chakrabortty, Jayato Nayak, Shirsendu Banerjee, and Maulin P. Shah individual chapters, the contributors.},
