	affiliations = {Department of Water Resources Engineering, Tarbiat Modares University, P.O. Box: 14115-139, Tehran, Iran; Agricultural Engineering Research Institute, Agricultural Research, Education and Extension Organization, Karaj, Alborz, Iran},
	abstract = {This study investigated the effects of diet change on reducing water consumption in Iran, while meeting its nutrition requirements. It also addresses how such a national policy could be effective at global scale in order to reduce water consumption. To address the issues, the concept of water footprint (WF) was employed for Iranian food basket which was divided into 12 groups. The evaluated diets included current (reference) diet, healthy recommended diet under the national food-based dietary guidelines and two optimized diets (minimized total consumption WF diet and minimized internal blue WF diet) with minimum deviation from the reference diet. It avoids, when possible, elimination of one or more food groups as this would be unacceptable for consumers and has not generally been considered in previous studies. The results of the minimized total consumption WF scenario showed a reduction of intake in food groups having low nutritional water productivity, such as red meat and vegetable oil, and an increase in, high nutritional water productivity food groups, such as wheat and vegetables. A similar pattern was followed for the minimized internal blue WF diet; however, greater reductions were applied to fruits and rice, which have high internal blue WF values. The minimized internal blue WF scenario reduced the internal blue WF by 7.5 BMC/yr. The minimized total consumption WF diet had no effect in this regard, but was effective at global scale and reduced the blue WF consumption by 4.5 BCM/yr. The modeling setup of this research work with high flexibility can be recommended as being applicable to similar research projects. © 2020},
