	affiliations = {Faculty of Environment and Resource Studies, Mahasarakham University, Mahasarakham 44000, Thailand; Centre for Process Integration and Intensification - CPI2, Research Institute of Chemical and Process Engineering - MÜKKI, University of Pannonia, 8200 Veszprém, Egyetem u.10, Hungary},
	abstract = {An integrated model for efficient biomass and bioenergy network optimization was used to calculate the footprints and costs for different technologies on rice husk-fuelled CHP production. These absolute footprint and cost values were normalized into relative values, and then plotted in the EPSM. The environmental and economic profiles of various technologies for rice husk-fuelled CHP were studied using a wider spectrum of technological options, including combustion, gasification, and pyrolysis systems. The indicators analyzed were the key environmental footprints associated with biomass and fossil energy sources, i.e., carbon, nitrogen, and water footprints, and were supplemented by the costs. The best option was pyrolysis and the use of oil as a substitute for coal in the conventional coal power plants. The results can be used as supporting information for decision making about appropriate biomass technology. This is an abstract of a paper presented at the CHISA 2012 - 20th International Congress of Chemical and Process Engineering and PRES 2012 - 15th Conference PRES (Prague, Czech Republic 8/25-29/2012).},
